*What inspired your team to get together and work on this project?
Our team had a strong desire to create a product in the hardware/robotics space that would be highly impactful and align with our skill sets.  We brainstormed many, many ideas and eventually came to 3D scanning.  We saw all of the excitement surrounding 3D printing, and thought that there should be similar excitement around 3D scanning, but that it wasn't there. We looking into 3D scanning more, and found that it had many exciting uses, but that costs prohibitively high cost and complexity kept its use restricted to large enterprises.  We realized that we could create an accurate, easy-to-use, low-cost solution that would put this technology into the hands of vastly more people than can currently access it.

*Who do you view as your competitors, and how do you differ from them?
Our competitors can be separated into 3 categories

The current lowest-cost high-accuracy options:
The major competitors in this range would be the NextEngine scanner or Artec's 3D scanners.  Our price will be much lower than these products, and our scanner will be easier to use than the NextEnginer scanner. The NextEngine costs over $3,000 (once you've purchased all the necessary software), and the least expensive Artec scanner costs $12,000. Our scanner's accuracy will be in the same range as these products.  Unlike these products, however, our scanner will only be able to scan objects that are under a certain size. While the Artec scanners make scaning of large objects fairly simple, the scanning large objects with the NextEngine is very inconvenient. That is similarly true for other products in that range. 

The very low-cost (free) options:
There are some options on the market that come in at a price lower than our.  AutoDesk as an free app called 123D Catch--you take a series of images of an object and then it performs image reconstruction to generate a 3D model. Some products (like Scanect) allow a customer to use a Kinect to perform 3D scanning, and Microsoft recently released KinectFusion, which turns the Kinect into a 3D scanner for anyone with the Windows Kinect SDK. These technologies, though, do not provide the level of accuracy we will.  They have more difficulty with highly specular objects than we will, and require user participation during the entire scanning process.

The emerging competitors:
There are a couple competitors that have announced products but don't have anything for sale yet.  CADScan successfully completed a Kickstarter project for a desktop 3D scanner that will be similar to ours in terms of target specifications and customers.  From the Kickstarter funding levels, it seems that they plan on charging at least Â£600 for the scanner, a price we are planning to come in significantly below.  MakerBot also just announced at SXSW that they will be producing a desktop 3D scanner called the Digitizer. It was very nebulous on details, but given their 3D printer costs and their description of the Digitizer, we guess that the will be charging over $1500.

*Who is your target customer? (Hint: "Everyone" is not the right answer.)
We are targeting individual consumers and small businesses.

Of individual consumers, we are targeting hobbyists, enthusiasts, and artists. Many people have gotten really excited about desktop 3D printing, and will be similarly excited by desktop 3D scanning.  There is evidence for this by CADScan's successful Kickstarter campaign, and the excitment surrounding MakerBot's SXSW Digitizer announcement. Though much of the popular focus has been on scanning objects in order to get a model to print, other uses of 3D scanners can be marketed. Maybe a young child wants to send his grandmother something he made, but she lives on the other side of the country; he could scan in his creation then send it to his grandmother, allowing her to enjoy it immediately.

Of small businesses, we will focus on research labs, product designers, and small manufacturers. In research labs, it is often important to have models and measurements of objects being tested; while the 3D scanners available today would be an un-affordable luxury, ours would be low-cost enough to be a practical purpose.  Product designers can make initial designs with physical materials, which are nicer to work with, and then scan them to get a usable CAD model. Small manufacturers and machine shops can use them in the same fashion that large manufacturers do: for automated verification of manufactured parts.

*Have you received any funding (including angels, family/friends, personal dollars invested, etc.)? Do you have any customers? (These two questions help us gauge your starting point, so don't worry, there is no "wrong answer.")
We have not received any funding so far. There has been a small amount of personal money spent for materials, but nothing very significant.

*We will have a lot of applications for this program, so choosing our final teams will be tough. Why do you think you should rise to the top? What sets you apart from other teams?
The aptitude of our team sets us apart. The team was chosen in order to assemble the skills necessary to successfully execute on a hardware startup, and it shows.  We have three dedicated, brilliant, and hard-working team members, each with their own unique technical skill set: programming and robotic systems, mechanical engineering and embedded systems, and optics and signal processing. We hustle to get customer desires from the source, and having the product vision needed to build a product that users want.

We have been working on this project over the semester as part of 6.S078, Entrepeneurship Project, and are excited to take it to the next level.
